04827nam a22005415i 9780520956711DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20132013cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209567117 a10.1525/97805209567112doi  a(DE-B1597)519651  a(OCoLC)863203808  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS786 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a951/.5051 aGoldstein, Melvyn C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA History of Modern Tibet, Volume 3 :bThe Storm Clouds Descend, 1955-1957 /cMelvyn C. Goldstein. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (588 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tGlossary of Key People and Terms -- tGanzi County Names in Tibetan and Chinese -- t1. First Steps -- t2. Pushback -- t3. Mao's "Socialist Transformation Campaign" and Democratic Reforms in Sichuan -- t4. The Khamba Uprising Begins -- t5. The Rise of Jenkhentsisum -- t6. Jenkhentsisum Expands and India Invites the Dalai Lama -- t7. The Mönlam Incident of 1956 and Its Aftermath -- t8. The Chinese Government Responds to the Uprising -- t9. The Preparatory Committee for the Tibet Autonomous Region (PCTAR) -- t10. Fan Ming's "Great Expansion" -- t11. The Dalai Lama Visits India -- t12. The Khambas, JKTS, and the CIA -- t13. The Dalai Lama Returns -- t14. The "Great Contraction" and the "Great Discontinuance" -- t15. Final Thoughts -- tAppendix A. Appeal of Thubten Nyenjik [JKTS] to the Queen of England -- tAppendix B. Correct Tibetan Spellings -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is not possible to fully understand contemporary politics between China and the Dalai Lama without understanding what happened in the 1950's. The third volume in Melvyn Goldstein's History of Modern Tibet series, The Calm before the Storm, examines the critical years of 1955 through 1957. During this period, the Preparatory Committee for a Tibet Autonomous Region was inaugurated in Lhasa, and a major Tibetan uprising occurred in Sichuan Province. Jenkhentsisum, a Tibetan anti-communist émigré group, emerged as an important player with secret links to Indian Intelligence, the Dalai Lama's Lord Chamberlain, the United States, and Taiwan. And in Tibet, Fan Ming, the acting head of the CCP's office in Lhasa, launched the "Great Expansion," which recruited many thousands of Han Cadres to Lhasa in preparation for beginning democratic reforms, only to be stopped decisively by Mao Zedong's "Great Contraction" which sent them back to China and ended talk of reforms in Tibet for the foreseeable future. In Volume III, Goldstein draws on never-before seen Chinese government documents, published and unpublished memoirs and diaries, and invaluable in-depth interviews with important Chinese and Tibetan participants (including the Dalai Lama) to offer a new level of insight into the events and principal players of the time. Goldstein corrects factual errors and misleading stereotypes in the history, and uncovers heretofore unknown information on the period to reveal in depth a nuanced portrait of Sino-Tibetan relations that goes far beyond anything previously imagined.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHISTORY / Asia / General. 0aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist). 0aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z9783110690